  "prompt": "What is voltage regulation formula?",
  "response": "The voltage regulation formula is used to determine the change in voltage between the no-load and full-load conditions of a power supply, transformer, or generator. It is typically expressed as a percentage and is given by:\n\n\\[\n\\text{Voltage Regulation} = \\frac{V_{\\text{no-load}} - V_{\\text{full-load}}}{V_{\\text{full-load}}} \\times 100\\%\n\\]\n\nWhere:\n- \\( V_{\\text{no-load}} \\) is the voltage at the output terminals when there is no load connected (open circuit).\n- \\( V_{\\text{full-load}} \\) is the voltage at the output terminals when the load is connected and drawing full current.\n\n### Notes:\n- Voltage regulation quantifies how well a device maintains its output voltage under varying load conditions.\n- A lower voltage regulation percentage indicates better performance, as it means the voltage remains more stable with changes in load.\n- This formula is commonly applied to transformers, generators, and voltage regulators in electrical systems.",
